		<header>
			
			<h1>New regional grains information portal launched in EAC</h1>

			
			<h4>
												28 September 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>At the end of July 2013, USAID announced the launch of “a regional information portal to track production and export of grains in the five East African Community (EAC) states in an effort to boost intraregional commodities trade (see 
<a href="http://www.rfbs.in/" target="_self">www.rfbs.in</a>). This online platform provides a “monthly regional food balance sheet based on production and export data supplied by industry players, paving the way for goods to move from surplus to deficit areas”. This is seen as important in the EAC, since there are always some areas harvesting when other parts are experiencing a deficit.</p><p>The aim is to enable the EAC states to meet regional grain needs from within the EAC before resorting to imports from outside the region. It is hoped that the new system will also promote grain price convergence across the EAC (see table for current price differences) and help stabilise both prices and supply within a common staple grains policy framework. It is also hoped that the information tool will avert the use of export bans in response to scares over supply.</p><p><b>Maize prices across the EAC per tonne (US dollars)</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
<td width="111" valign="top">  Location
  </td><td width="95" valign="top">  Kampala
  </td><td width="95" valign="top">  Kigali
  </td><td width="95" valign="top">  Dar es Salaam
  </td><td width="95" valign="top">  Nairobi
  </td><td width="95" valign="top">  Burundi
  </td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width="111" valign="top">  Price
  </td><td width="95" valign="top">  256
  </td><td width="95" valign="top">  325
  </td><td width="95" valign="top">  340
  </td><td width="95" valign="top">  362
  </td><td width="95" valign="top">  392
  </td>
</tr>

</table>
<p>Source: Regional Agricultural Trade Intelligence Network (RATIN), cited in <i>Businessdailyafrica.com</i>, 30 July 2013 (see below)</p><p>Earlier in July, the national regulatory authorities of the EAC “approved harmonised regional standards for 18 grains”, a move intended to boost intra-regional trade in the grains concerned by allowing cross-border trade without any need for further testing. A certified certificate of origin for consignments under US$2,000 has also been agreed.</p><p>In early August, it was reported that Kenyan millers were importing increased volumes of maize from their EAC neighbours Uganda and Tanzania, having already purchased some 300,000 tonnes. These purchases have served to stabilise Kenyan prices: maize meal prices in Nairobi are reported to have fallen by about 15% since February 2013.</p><p>This trade needs to be seen against the background of the 50% import duty charged on non-EAC maize. While impending harvests should further serve to ease the maize supply situation in Kenya, an outbreak of Lethal Necrosis, a viral disease, is expected to affect production levels. &nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Business Daily Africa</i>, ‘USAID sets up website for EAC to track grain exports’, 30 July 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/US+agency+sets+up+website+for+EAC+to+track+grain+exports+/-/539546/1931848/-/evhe56z/-/index.html" target="_self">http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/US+agency+sets+up+website+for+EAC+to+...</a></p><p>&nbsp;<i>Business Daily Africa</i>, ‘Millers import maize from EAC to bridge deficit’, 8 August 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Millers-import-maize-from-EAC-to-bridge-deficit/-/539552/1941450/-/adqanaz/-/index.html" target="_self">http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Millers-import-maize-from-EAC-to-brid...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The initiative in the EAC is similar to earlier market information system initiatives launched in Eastern and Southern Africa. These include the Regional Agricultural Trade Intelligence Network (RATIN), a service launched by the Eastern Africa Grain Council (EAGC) and the Food and Agriculture Market Information System (FAMIS) set up by COMESA over the period 2005–2010. The EAGC service faced problems arising from major inconsistencies in the application of agricultural trade policy measures (e.g. the use of import and export bans) in response to national food security concerns.</p><p>The broader FAMIS scheme targeted large-scale traders who were expected to move significant quantities of agricultural products from surplus to deficit areas in the COMESA region, but COMESA faced problems in securing timely and regular data, which served to compromise the ability of the system to support actual trade.</p><p>It is unclear how the new USAID-supported scheme will overcome the constraints experienced by similar schemes in the past. These constraints critically relate to the effectiveness of ongoing efforts to harmonise SPS measures and other standards required for grain to flow smoothly across regional borders without additional costs and delays being incurred.</p><p>If the constraints of the previous schemes are to be overcome, then any USAID initiative involving improved market information systems will also need to get to grips with substantive issues facing the grain trade in the EAC. These include:</p>
<ul>

<li>tariff and non-tariff barriers (SPS measures, grain standards, etc.); </li>

<li>trade finance; </li>

<li>infrastructure constraints (such as warehousing); </li>

<li>the high costs of transportation. </li>

</ul>
<p>Dealing with market information systems alone is unlikely to achieve significant results, leaving a situation where most of the grain moved across borders continues to be traded through informal channels.</p>
		</div>
		
